      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely right to be concerned about security, and the good news is that your money is generally very safe in these accounts because they are held in a bank, not a mutual fund or crypto exchange. Most banks in the US are insured by the FDIC (or NCUA for credit unions), which guarantees up to $250,000 per depositor per institution against bank failure. Even if the bank goes under, you get your money back. It's a very stable place to keep your emergency fund, much like a standard brick-and-mortar bank, provided you don't leave it in a single bank that might not have enough capital to cover all deposits in a crisis.\n\nHowever, since you have $15,000, you should consider diversifying your savings across 2 or 3 different banks to ensure you stay under the $250,000 insurance limit for each specific institution. This is a standard safety practice known as \"banking diversification.\" If you keep your entire $15k in just one place, you are fully covered, but spreading it out is a prudent habit for any long-term saver.\n\nAs for the security of the actual *data* and",
